#Text=Walter Calverley
#Text=For other people named Main Page , see Main Page ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Canting arms of Calverley : Argent , a fess gules between three calves passant sable [ 1 ]
#Text=Walter Calverley ( died 1605 ) was an English squire and murderer .
#Text=His story became the basis of more than one literary work of the early 17th century .
#Text=Early life
#Text=Walter Calverley was the eldest son and heir of William Calverley ( d.1572 ) by his wife , Katherine Thorneholme , daughter of John Thorneholme of Haysthorpe , Yorkshire .

#Text=William Calverley was the son of Sir Walter Calverley and Anne Danby , daughter of Sir Christopher Danby ( d. 14 June 1571 ) and Elizabeth Neville , daughter of Richard Neville , 2nd Baron Latimer . [ 2 ]
#Text=The Calverleys were lords of the manors of Calverley and Pudsey , Yorkshire .
#Text=His father died when he was a boy .
#Text=He inherited land at Burley-in-Wharfedale , Fagley , Farsley , Eccleshill , Bolton , and Seacroft ; a relative of William Brooke , 10th Baron Cobham , became his guardian .
#Text=He studied at Clare Hall , Cambridge from 5 May 1579 , matriculating on 1 October , but he was there only a short time and took no degree .
#Text=He became engaged to the daughter of a neighbour in Yorkshire . [ 3 ]
#Text=Marriage , crime and death
#Text=When Calverley visited London , his guardian insisted on his breaking this engagement and on his marrying Philippa , a granddaughter of Lord Cobham .
#Text=Calverley went back to Calverley Hall with his wife , whom he disliked , and adopted a lifestyle revolving around drinking and gambling .
#Text=He soon ran through all his money . [ 3 ]
#Text=On 23 April 1605 , he received news that a relative , a student at Cambridge , had been arrested for a debt for which he himself was responsible .

#Text=In a drunken frenzy , he rushed at his two eldest children , William and Walter , the former four years old and the latter 18 months ( baptised at Calverley on 4 October 1603 ) and killed them both ; at the same time he stabbed his wife , but not fatally .

#Text=He then rode off to a neighbouring village where a third infant son , Henry , was out at nurse , intending to kill him as well , but he was stopped on the road and taken before Sir John Savile , a magistrate , who committed him to prison at Wakefield .
#Text=After some delay he was brought to trial at York in August following ; he declined to plead , and was therefore pressed to death in York Castle on 5 August . [ 3 ]
#Text=Aftermath
#Text=Calverley 's widow remarried Sir Thomas Burton of Stokerston , Leicestershire . [ 3 ]
#Text=His estates escaped forfeiture and descended to his surviving son Henry , later a royalist and fined under the Commonwealth .
#Text=He was the last of the family to reside regularly at Calverley Hall .
#Text=He married , first , Elizabeth , daughter of John Moore of Grantham ; secondly , Joyce , daughter of Sir Walter Pye .
#Text=He died on 1 January 1661 , and was succeeded by a son Walter , who was knighted by Charles II in consideration of his father 's loyalty .
#Text=In literature
#Text=Title page of A Yorkshire Tragedy ( 1608 )
#Text=Calverley 's position gave his crime wide notoriety .
#Text=On 12 June Nathaniel Butter published a popular tract on the subject , which was followed on 24 August by an account of Calverley 's death .
#Text=A ballad was also issued by another publisher , Thomas Pavier , at the same time .

#Text=Calverley 's story was twice dramatised — first by George Wilkins in Miseries of Enforced Marriage ( 1607 ) , and , secondly , in A Yorkshire Tragedy which was first published by Pavier in 1608 , under the title A Yorkshire Tragedy - not so new as lamentable and true : written by W. Shakspeare .

#Text=The latter was included in the third and fourth folios of William Shakespeare 's works ( 1664 and 1685 ) , but is no longer considered to be his work ( modern scholarship generally favouring Thomas Middleton ) . [ 3 ]
#Text=Aphra Behn reworked The Miseries of Enforced Marriage into her 1676 play , The Town Fop or , Sir Timothy Tawdry . [ 4 ]
